You can run soap web service with embedded jetty by override default HttpServerProvider property. Make sure that you have added [jetty-http-spi][1] jar file on classpath

    System.setProperty(&quot;com.sun.net.httpserver.HttpServerProvider&quot;, &quot;org.eclipse.jetty.http.spi.JettyHttpServerProvider&quot;);

org.eclipse.jetty.http.spi.JettyHttpServerProvider is an [implementation of Java HTTP Server SPI][2] provided by [Jetty][3]

You can verify if the server running is jetty by looking at Server response header.
This code worked for me

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        ContentWsImplement contentImplement = new ContentWsImplement();
        System.setProperty(&quot;com.sun.net.httpserver.HttpServerProvider&quot;, &quot;org.eclipse.jetty.http.spi.JettyHttpServerProvider&quot;);
        Endpoint.publish(&quot;http://0.0.0.0:8000/services/getcontent&quot;, contentImplement);
    }


  [1]: https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/org.eclipse.jetty/jetty-http-spi
  [2]: http://java.sun.com/javase/6/docs/jre/api/net/httpserver/spec/index.html
  [3]: https://archive.eclipse.org/jetty/7.6.0.RC5/apidocs/org/eclipse/jetty/http/spi/JettyHttpServerProvider.html

